<a name="0">[0]</a> <a href="#0" id=0>A knowledge flow spiral can generate and generalize knowledge during the processing and recycling of knowledge.</a>
<a name="1">[1]</a> <a href="#1" id=1>However, the knowledge flow network evolves in a more complex and dynamic way.</a>
<a name="2">[2]</a> <a href="#2" id=2>self-replication happens in the nodes of hypercycles while external knowledge flow is between nodes of a knowledge flow spiral, and catalytic support happens between nodes while internal knowledge flow is within individual nodes of a knowledge flow spiral.</a>
<a name="3">[3]</a> <a href="#3" id=3>The self-replication and catalytic-support arcs in the hypercycle correspond to the external knowledge flow and internal knowledge flow of the knowledge spiral.</a>
<a name="4">[4]</a> <a href="#4" id=4>Maintaining openness is a strategy for the sustainable development of knowledge flow within a research community.</a>
<a name="5">[5]</a> <a href="#5" id=5>Reflecting the development of a discipline, the distribution of knowledge energy in a network changes as its citation network evolves.</a>
<a name="6">[6]</a> <a href="#6" id=6>Enhancing inflow, that is, selecting the appropriate higher-energy nodes to cooperate, is a strategy to increase the efficiency of knowledge flow networking.</a>
<a name="7">[7]</a> <a href="#7" id=7>(2) Internal knowledge flow u'\u2014' knowledge arising within a node as the result of processing.</a>
